","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1484–1550":"1484–1550","1485–1550":"1485–1550","1489–1544":"1489–1544","1480–1551":"1480–1551","1480–1556":"1480–1556","1510–1576":"1510–1576","1466–1506":"1466–1506","1467–1533":"1467–1533","18 February 1487":"18 februari 1487","1484":"1484","1550":"1550","1480":"1480","8 November 1506":"8 november 1506","1556":"1556","1533":"1533","1467":"1467","1544":"1544","1489":"1489","1510":"1510","1466":"1466","1576":"1576","about 1504":"circa 1504","1551":"1551","1485":"1485","10 July 1533":"10 juli 1533","1506":"1506","1549":"1549","Leicestershire, England":"Leicestershire, England","Holy Trinity, Ashby de la Zouch, Leicestershire, England":"Holy Trinity Church, Ashby de la Zouch, Leicestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England","London, England":"London, England","Stockbury, Kent, England":"Stockbury, Kent, England","England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1484–1550":"1484–1550","1485–1550":"1485–1550","1489–1544":"1489–1544","1480–1551":"1480–1551","1480–1556":"1480–1556","1510–1576":"1510–1576","1466–1506":"1466–1506","1467–1533":"1467–1533","18 February 1487":"18 February 1487","1484":"1484","1550":"1550","1480":"1480","8 November 1506":"8 November 1506","1556":"1556","1533":"1533","1467":"1467","1544":"1544","1489":"1489","1510":"1510","1466":"1466","1576":"1576","about 1504":"about 1504","1551":"1551","1485":"1485","10 July 1533":"10 July 1533","1506":"1506","1549":"1549","Leicestershire, England":"Leicestershire, England","Holy Trinity, Ashby de la Zouch, Leicestershire, England":"Holy Trinity Church, Ashby de la Zouch, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","London, England":"London, England","Stockbury, Kent, England":"Stockbury, Kent, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hastings","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: habitational name from Hastings (Sussex), near which the English army was defeated by the Normans in 1066. The placename derives from an Old English personal name <i>Hǣsta</i> + the Old English groupname suffix <i>-ingas</i>. In the latter part of the 12th century, at the time of William the Lion, the surname was taken to Scotland, where it assimilated instances of the native Scottish surname <b>Harestane</b>.","English: variant of   Hasting   with Middle English genitival <i>-s</i>.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hOistín</b> ‘descendant of <i>Oistín</i>’, the Gaelic form of the personal name <i>Augustine</i> (see   Austin  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Hasting","meanings":["English: from the Norman personal name <i>Hastang</i>, <i>Hastenc</i>, <i>Hasten</i> (Old Norse <i>Hásteinn</i> ‘high’ + ‘stone’). See also   Hastings  ."]},{"name":"Heston","meanings":["English: habitational name from Heston (Middlesex) or Histon (Cambridgeshire). The Middlesex placename derives from Old English <i>hǣs</i> ‘brushwood’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, while the Cambridgeshire placename may derive from Old English <i>hyse</i> ‘shoot, tendril’, also ‘son, youth’, + <i>tūn</i>.","Irish (Mayo): variant of   Hastings  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":65,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Hastings was born in 1484, in England, her father, Baron Edward Hastings, was 18 and her mother, Mary Hungerford, was 17. She married Thomas Stanley about 1504, in England, United Kingdom. She died in 1550, at the age of 66."},"et":{"1484–1550":"1484–1550","1485–1550":"1485–1550","1489–1544":"1489–1544","1480–1551":"1480–1551","1480–1556":"1480–1556","1510–1576":"1510–1576","1466–1506":"1466–1506","1467–1533":"1467–1533","18 February 1487":"18. veebruar 1487","1484":"1484","1550":"1550","1480":"1480","8 November 1506":"8. november 1506","1556":"1556","1533":"1533","1467":"1467","1544":"1544","1489":"1489","1510":"1510","1466":"1466","1576":"1576","about 1504":"umbes 1504","1551":"1551","1485":"1485","10 July 1533":"10. juuli 1533","1506":"1506","1549":"1549","Leicestershire, England":"Leicestershire, England","Holy Trinity, Ashby de la Zouch, Leicestershire, England":"Holy Trinity Church, Ashby de la Zouch, Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","London, England":"London, England","Stockbury, Kent, England":"Stockbury, Kent, England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1484–1550":"1484–1550","1485–1550":"1485–1550","1489–1544":"1489–1544","1480–1551":"1480–1551","1480–1556":"1480–1556","1510–1576":"1510–1576","1466–1506":"1466–1506","1467–1533":"1467–1533","18 February 1487":"18. helmikuuta 1487","1484":"1484","1550":"1550","1480":"1480","8 November 1506":"8. marraskuuta 1506","1556":"1556","1533":"1533","1467":"1467","1544":"1544","1489":"1489","1510":"1510","1466":"1466","1576":"1576","about 1504":"noin 1504","1551":"1551","1485":"1485","10 July 1533":"10. heinäkuuta 1533","1506":"1506","1549":"1549","Leicestershire, England":"Leicestershire, England","Holy Trinity, Ashby de la Zouch, Leicestershi